1) Introduction: The Crime Analysis task¶

This section should be written in markdown.

1. Give the background to the "Drugs and Guns" project. Use the academic literature to motivate the work. Remember to cite papers you are using.
2. Give the aims and objectives of the project in your own words. (Do not copy the assignment spec)
3. Outline the technical approach (what you plan to do)

The role that weapons and drugs play in causing physical harm is both devastating and pervasive. Gun context (e.g., hunting vs. assault weapons) and individual familiarity with weapons are thought to have an impact on this "priming" effect of firearms[2], suggesting a potential degradative effect of this phenomenon among frequent gun users and a heightened potential for weapon effects among societies with lower levels of weapon availability[1]. As drug abuse increases, some people use crimes such as robbery to find items that can be stolen and sold to others to raise money to buy more drugs. Some resort to more serious crimes such as robbery, theft, and extortion. All this is to secure funds for purchasing drugs. Some turn to business to increase their income, but being caught by the police can result in greater penalties by the courts[3]. The firearms that are most commonly used illegally in the UK include pistols, revolvers, and shotguns. Unlawfully modified, reactivated, or converted guns are used in a significant proportion of shootings. This also applies to blank guns with firing modifications. The bulk of shootings in the UK are carried out by street gangs that engage in a variety of criminal activities, including drug dealing and armed robbery[4].

In this notebook, we perform crime analysis using various large datasets such as Street Level Crime Data published by the UK Home Office and English Indices of Deprivation Data. To store and process provided big dataset, we use Microsoft's public cloud computing platform, Microsoft Azure. Big data analysis and visualization are made easy with Spark SQL running on data stored in Azure. Spark's interactive analytics capabilities are fast enough to run exploratory queries without sampling. Combine Spark with visualization tools to interactively process and visualize complex data sets[5]

To evaluate whether the rate of crime is rising or falling, time series analysis, the ADF test, and the stationarity test can be employed. Time-series decomposition can be used to identify the crime's annual trend. Additionally, the correlation may be used to identify a link between drug use and firearm, and the correlation can then be validated through the development of a regression model. Due to its ability to hold records in memory while performing operations, Spark provides exceptional performance for iterative queries typical of machine learning workloads.

Data preparation¶

The data source path has been saved in the first cell so that it can be easily changed. Although it has been placed by default in a folder called "DataPath", this can be changed by altering the datasource variable. Two data files are used, including "all_crimes18_hdr.txt.gz" which contains approximately 43 million reported and recorded crimes from 2010 to 2017 and "LSOA_pop_v2.csv" (Lower Layer Super Output Area, UK Office for National Statistics).

Use the Spark session to read the dataset. The 'csv' function is specified as a parameter in the 'spark.read.format()' since the provided dataset is in CSV format. Spark SQL is used to handle the data, while dataframes are utilised to store the data (together with pandas dataframes for visualisation).

To calculate the number of firearm incidents per capita for Birmingham, first, remove all null values from the data set because the data frame is immutable. Therefore, applying a filter that removes non-null values creates a new data frame that does not contain records with null values.The number of firearm incidents is calculated by aggregating the cities and dividing by each city's total population to get the desired characteristic.

lsoa = lsoa.select(col("geography"),col("geography code"),col("Variable: All usual residents; measures: Value"))
lsoa = lsoa.withColumnRenamed("Variable: All usual residents; measures: Value","resident")
lsoa_df = lsoa.withColumn("geography",regexp_extract(lsoa['geography'], '[a-zA-Z]+',0))
lsoa_df.na.drop() 
allcrime_df = allcrime.withColumn("LSOA name",regexp_extract(allcrime['LSOA name'],'[a-zA-Z]+',0))
allcrime_firearm = allcrime_df.select("LSOA code","LSOA name","Crime type").\
                 filter((col('Crime type')=='Possession of weapons') & \
                        (col('Last outcome category')=='Offender sent to prison'))
allcrime_firearm = allcrime_firearm.withColumnRenamed("LSOA name","city")
allcrime_df.na.drop()

Crime Analysis using Time Series¶

A trend is the long-term direction of a time series. This component is typically increasing, decreasing, or constant. Seasonality is the periodic behaviour of a time series that occurs within a year. Residuals represent what is behind seasonality and trend decoupling from a time series. In other words, what the model cannot explain is the variability in the data[7]. We can automatically decompose the time series using the seasonal decompose function from statsmodels package.

In [22]:
decomposition = sm.tsa.seasonal_decompose(crimes_pdf['count'], model='additive',extrapolate_trend='freq')
fig = decomposition.plot()
fig.set_size_inches(14,7)
plt.show()

The first graph represents the original time series. The second chart represents the trend of the time series model extracted from the original time series. Finally, the third and fourth plots show the seasonality and residual components of the same time series. Here, it shows that violent crimes such as "gun possession" and "violent/sexual crimes" are increasing trend. The repeating pattern for the seasonal component has a repeating period of one year. This shows that different seasons or seasons affect violent crime. The residual plot does not reveal any discernible patterns. We may thus conclude that the components of our time series were properly decomposed[7].

Decomposition gives a very clear picture of trends and makes time series interpretation easier and more reliable. As we saw with the line plot before, there is a very slight decrease in violent crimes from 2011 to 2013, after which there is a continuous rise until 2019. Following that, we see that violent crime tends to stabilise until the conclusion of the research period in 2021.

Time Series Plot with Rolling Average¶

When plotting time series data, these fluctuations can obscure the peaks and troughs of the plot. So, in order to draw distinct values from the data, we use the concept of rolling average concept to create a time series graph. The simple mean of the most recent "n" data is the rolling average or moving average. It can assist us in identifying tendencies that might otherwise be difficult to locate. They can also be employed to identify long-term patterns. The rolling average may be calculated by adding together the past 'n' values and dividing them by 'n'. In contrast, Nan would be the first (n-1) value of the rolling average[6].

In [23]:
def stationarity(timeseries, title):
    plt.clf()
    #Determing rolling statistics
    rolmean = pd.Series(timeseries).rolling(window=10).mean() 
    rolstd = pd.Series(timeseries).rolling(window=10).std()
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16, 4))
    ax.plot(timeseries, label= title)
    ax.plot(rolmean, label='rolling mean');
    ax.plot(rolstd, label='rolling std (x10)');
    ax.legend()
    plt.show()
In [24]:
pd.options.display.float_format = '{:.8f}'.format
stationarity(crimes_pd['count'],'raw data')

<Figure size 640x480 with 0 Axes>

Here we are using window size = 7. This is the moving average represented by the red line that clearly demonstrates an increasing tendency. In addition, the previously observed slight trend slump at the beginning and steady action towards the end can also be seen in the moving averages. This validates insights from line charts and time series decompositions.

The analysis's primary goal concerned the assertion that violent crimes are rising in the UK. Only violent crimes are used for this, and the total number of crimes is then shown using a bar graph. However, we only have a general sense of the various offences and their number from 2011 to 2021. after which a line plot with regard to the years was attempted. This provides the general trend for the specified time period. Time series analysis was performed to filter out the data as trend, seasonality, and noise independently in order to better comprehend the pattern. From the decomposition, we have learned the seasonal behaviour of your data within an uptrend., we were also able to obtain clear trend lines to analyze general trends in violent crime during the study period. Rolling averages and Rolling standard deviations add more information rather than giving complete information about a time series like decomposition. However, forecasting is not available for regular time series analysis. The ARIMAX forecasting approach, however, may be used to anticipate data that is stationary or non-stationary and multivariate with any form of data patterns, such as level, trend, seasonality, or cyclicity[7].

To assess the claim that Birmingham has more shootings per capita than anywhere else in the UK, The firearm incident count is evaluated by aggregating by city and this number is divided by the total population in each city to generate the necessary feature. utilised the seaborn package, which is superior to matplotlib in handling Pandas data frames and representing graphs more attractively, to visualise the data.

Investigation of the connection between drug offences and firearm events is done using linear regression analysis.Similar to how drug incidents are analysed, the number of firearm incidents is aggregated by city and divided by each city's total population before being used to determine the number of incidents. The Regression line scatter plot is used to representing that these features are correlated.A linear regression model was created in the end to validate the association. However, the R2 score is less than 0.7, indicating that the predictive model is poor.
